animo is quite in place, though most editors bracket the word. It repeats the idea contained in taciti: cp. Lucr. v, 1090, Illud in his rebus tacitus ue forte requiras. Cicero is asking the jurors not to place counter-arguments before their own minds (taciti) as he went along ; but, when they came to consider their verdict, to ‘mentally demand that any real omission he might have made should be supplied.’ Not till he reached the end of the case was his audience to be at liberty to decide that he had not met every objection, or that he had ‘burked' any essential point.
